Introduction

This vignette presents an analysis of Bitcoin price prediction using various time series models. The primary objective is to compare the effectiveness of different models based on their forecasting accuracy.

Methodology

In this section, we describe the models used for prediction, including SARIMA and GARCH model’s.

Time Series Models

  • SARIMA: Seasonal Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average.
  • GARCH: Generalized Autoregressive Conditional Heteroskedasticity.

Data Description

The dataset used for this analysis is from the ‘XXBTZUSD’ pair, retrieved from [source]. The data includes time-stamped prices over different intervals (1 minute, 5 minutes, 1 hour, 1 day).

API key and secret

load_api_keys <- function () {
api_key <- Sys.getenv (" KRAKEN_API_KEY ")
api_secret <- Sys.getenv (" KRAKEN_API_SECRET ")
return ( list ( key = api_key , secret = api_secret ) )
}

initialize_kraken_api <- function () {
keys <- load_api_keys ()
list (
key = api_key,
secret = api_secret)
}
get_ohlc_data <- function(pair = "XXBTZUSD", interval = 1440) {
  # Initialize Kraken API
  api <- initialize_kraken_api()

  # Kraken API endpoint
  url <- "https://api.kraken.com/0/public/OHLC"

  # Parameters for the request
  params <- list(
    pair = pair,
    interval = interval
  )

  # Make the GET request
  response <- GET(url, query = params)
  # Check the status code
  if (status_code(response) != 200) {
    stop("Failed to fetch data from Kraken API. Status code: ", status_code(response))
  }

  # Parse the response
  content <- fromJSON(content(response, "text"), flatten = TRUE)

  # Extract OHLC data
  ohlc_data <- content$result[[pair]]

  if (is.null(ohlc_data)) {
    stop("No data found for the given pair.")
  }

  # Convert to data frame
  ohlc_df <- as.data.frame(ohlc_data)
  colnames(ohlc_df) <- c("time", "open", "high", "low", "close", "vwap", "volume", "count")

  # Convert time from UNIX timestamp to readable date
  ohlc_df$time <- as.POSIXct(as.integer(ohlc_df$time),origin="1970-01-01",
        tryformats = "%Y-%m-%d")

  return(ohlc_df)
}

Make the data stationary

Stationary_data<-function(BTC,data=FALSE){
# Transform the BTC data
stationary=CalculateReturns((as.ts(BTC$close)),method = 'compound')[-1]
# Test for stationarity
test_adf=adf.test(stationary)
difference_logic = ifelse(test_adf$p.value > 0.05,'Differencing required','Data is stationary' )

# Return transformed data or check the stationary of the data
if (data){
  stationary
}
else{
  print(test_adf)
  print(difference_logic)
}

}

Plot_test<-function(BTC){
# Plot the acf and PACF plot
ggtsdisplay(BTC,main ='Original series')
ggtsdisplay(BTC^2,main ='Squared series')

# Check for Serial correlation
Serial_corr=Box.test(BTC,lag=10, type = "Ljung-Box")

# Determine if the mean != 0
T_Test =t.test(BTC,mu=0)

return(list(Serial_Correlation=Serial_corr,
            Sample_T_test=T_Test
            ))

}

# Function to calculate SMAPE
smape <- function(true, pred) {
  return(100 * mean(2 * abs(pred - true) / (abs(pred) + abs(true))))
}

# Function to fit multiple time series models and rank them
fit_time_series_models <- function(BTC, train_size = 0.8) {
  # Split the data into train/test sets
  train_index <- floor(train_size * length(BTC))
  train_data <- BTC[1:train_index]
  test_data <- BTC[(train_index + 1):length(BTC)]
  
  # Initialize an empty tibble to store results
  results <- tibble(Order = list(),
                    Model_name = character(),
                    Model = list(),
                    Error = logical(),
                    IC = double(),
                    SMAPE = double())
  
  # Step 1: Fitting SARIMA model
  tryCatch({  
  sarima_model <- auto.arima(train_data,seasonal = TRUE)
  sarima_forecast <- forecast(sarima_model, h = length(test_data))$mean
  sarima_ic <- AIC(sarima_model)
  sarima_smape <- smape(test_data, sarima_forecast)
  
  results <- results %>%
    add_row(Order = list(arimaorder(sarima_model)),
            Model_name = "SARIMA",
            Model = list(sarima_model),
            Error = FALSE,
            IC = sarima_ic,
            SMAPE = sarima_smape)
  },
  error = function(e) {
  # Handle the error (e.g., log it, print a message, or update results with an error flag)
  message("Error in SARIMA model fitting: ", e$message)
  results <- results %>%
    add_row(Order = NA,
            Model_name = "SARIMA",
            Model = list(sarima_model),
            Error = TRUE,
            IC = NA,
            SMAPE = NA)
})
  # Step 2: Fitting GARCH models
  list_garchModels = c("sGARCH","eGARCH","gjrGARCH")
  for (model_name in list_garchModels) {
  tryCatch({
     garch_spec <- ugarchspec(variance.model = list(model = model_name),
                           mean.model = list(armaOrder = c(0, 0)))
     garch_model <- ugarchfit(spec = garch_spec, data = train_data)
     garch_forecast <- ugarchforecast(garch_model, n.ahead = length(test_data))@forecast$seriesFor
     garch_ic <- infocriteria(garch_model)['Akaike',]
     garch_smape <- smape(test_data, garch_forecast)
  
  results <- results %>%
    add_row(Order = list(garch_model@model$modelinc),
            Model_name = model_name,
            Model =list(garch_model),
            Error = FALSE,
            IC = garch_ic,
            SMAPE = garch_smape)
  },
  error = function(e) {
  # Handle the error (e.g., log it, print a message, or update results with an error flag)
  message(glue("Error in {model_name} model fitting: "), e$message)
  results <- results %>%
    add_row(Order = NA,
            Model_name = glue("{model_name}"),
            Model =list(garch_model),
            Error = TRUE,
            IC = NA,
            SMAPE = NA)
  })
  }
  # Step 3: Fitting FGARCH models
  list_fgarchModel = c("NGARCH","NAGARCH","APARCH")
  for (model_name in list_fgarchModel) {
  tryCatch({
     fgarch_spec <-  ugarchspec(variance.model = list(model = "fGARCH", garchOrder=c(1,1),submodel =model_name), mean.model = list(armaOrder = c(0,0)))
     fgarch_model <- ugarchfit(spec = fgarch_spec, data = train_data)
     fgarch_forecast <- ugarchforecast(fgarch_model, n.ahead = length(test_data))@forecast$seriesFor
     fgarch_ic <- infocriteria(fgarch_model)['Akaike',]
     fgarch_smape <- smape(test_data, fgarch_forecast)
  
  results <- results %>%
    add_row(Order = list(garch_model@model$modelinc),
            Model_name = model_name,
             Model =list(fgarch_model),
            Error = FALSE,
            IC = garch_ic,
            SMAPE = garch_smape)
  },
  error = function(e) {
  # Handle the error (e.g., log it, print a message, or update results with an error flag)
  message(glue("Error in {model_name} model fitting: "), e$message)
  results <- results %>%
    add_row(Order = NA,
            Model_name = glue("{model_name}"),
             Model =NA,
            Error = TRUE,
            IC = NA,
            SMAPE = NA)
  })
  }
  ranked_results <- results %>% arrange(desc(IC),SMAPE)
  return(ranked_results)
}

Extract the fitted returns

Returns_value <- function(BTC, train_size = 0.8) {
  # Split the data into train/test sets
  train_index <- floor(train_size * length(BTC))
  train_data <- BTC[1:train_index]
  test_data <- BTC[(train_index + 1):length(BTC)]
  
  # Create an empty list to store the forecast values
  list_forecast<-list()
  
  # Step 1: Fitting SARIMA model
   
  sarima_model <- auto.arima(train_data,seasonal = TRUE)
  sarima_forecast <- forecast(sarima_model, h = length(test_data))$mean
  # Append the forecast to the list
  list_forecast<- c(list(sarima_forecast))

  # Step 2: Fitting GARCH models
  list_garchModels = c("sGARCH","eGARCH","gjrGARCH")
  for (model_name in list_garchModels) {
  
     garch_spec <- ugarchspec(variance.model = list(model = model_name),
                           mean.model = list(armaOrder = c(0, 0)))
     garch_model <- ugarchfit(spec = garch_spec, data = train_data)
     garch_forecast <- ugarchforecast(garch_model, n.ahead = length(test_data))
     list_forecast<-c(list_forecast,list(garch_forecast))
     
    }
  # Step 3: Fitting FGARCH models
  list_fgarchModel = c("NGARCH","NAGARCH","APARCH")
  for (model_name in list_fgarchModel) {

     fgarch_spec <-  ugarchspec(variance.model = list(model = "fGARCH", garchOrder=c(1,1),submodel =model_name), mean.model = list(armaOrder = c(0,0)))
     fgarch_model <- ugarchfit(spec = fgarch_spec, data = train_data)
     fgarch_forecast <- ugarchforecast(fgarch_model, n.ahead = length(test_data))@forecast$seriesFor
     list_forecast<-c(list_forecast,list(fgarch_forecast))
  
  
  }
  return(list_forecast)
}
names_model <-c(Models$Model_name)

Function to backtest trading strategy and generate plot

# Split the data into train/test sets
train_size = 0.8
  train_index <- floor(train_size * length(BTC_stationary))

  test_data <- BTC_stationary[(train_index + 1):length(BTC_stationary)]
  
backtest_strategy <- function(actual_returns, prediction_list, model_names) {
  results <- list()  # Store results in a list
  
  for (i in model_names) {
    predicted_returns <- prediction_list[[i]]
    
    # If predicted_returns is an S4 object, try to extract the fitted values or forecasts
    if (isS4(predicted_returns)) { 
      # For GARCH model predictions (ugarchforecast)
      if (inherits(predicted_returns, "ugarchforecast")) {
        predicted_returns <- fitted(predicted_returns)  # Extract fitted values
      }
      # For ARIMA or other models with forecast objects
      else if (inherits(predicted_returns, "forecast")) {
        predicted_returns <- predicted_returns$mean  # Extract mean forecasts
      } else {
        warning(paste("Unknown S4 class for model:", i, "- Skipping"))
        next  # Skip this iteration if the class is unknown
      }
    }
    
    # Convert to vector if it's still not numeric
    predicted_returns <- as.vector(predicted_returns)
    
    # Simple trading strategy: Buy if predicted return is positive, sell otherwise
    trading_signal <- ifelse(predicted_returns > 0, 1, -1)
    
    # Calculate returns from the strategy
    strategy_returns <- trading_signal * actual_returns
    
    # Cumulative returns for strategy and actual
    cumulative_strategy_returns <- cumsum(strategy_returns)
    cumulative_actual_returns <- cumsum(actual_returns)
    
    # Total return of the strategy
    total_return_strategy <- tail(cumulative_strategy_returns, 1)
    
    # Create a backtesting plot
    df <- data.frame(
      Time = 1:length(actual_returns),
      Strategy = cumulative_strategy_returns,
      Actual = cumulative_actual_returns
    )
    
    plot <- ggplot(df, aes(x = Time)) +
      geom_line(aes(y = Strategy, color = "Strategy")) +
      geom_line(aes(y = Actual, color = "Actual")) +
      labs(title = paste("Backtesting:", i, "Strategy vs. Actual Returns"), y = "Cumulative Returns") +
      scale_color_manual("", values = c("Strategy" = "blue", "Actual" = "red"))
    
    # Store the plot and total return for the current model in the result list
    results[[i]] <- list(plot = plot, total_return = total_return_strategy)
  }
  
  return(results)  # Return all the results
}

backtest_output<-backtest_strategy(test_data,Return_data,names_model)

Combined function

intergrate_function<-function(Pair,Interval,train_size=0.8){
  # Get the data using API
  newdata<-get_ohlc_data(pair=Pair,interval = Interval)
  
  # Clean data
  newdata %>% mutate_if(is.character,as.numeric) %>% mutate(time=as.Date(time))->data
  # Stationary the data
  data_stationary<-Stationary_data(data,data=TRUE)
  # Split the data into train/test sets
  train_index <- floor(train_size * length(data_stationary))
  train_data <- data_stationary[1:train_index]
  test_data <- data_stationary[(train_index + 1):length(data_stationary)]
  # Create SMAPE
  smape <- function(true, pred) {
  return(100 * mean(2 * abs(pred - true) / (abs(pred) + abs(true))))
  }
  # Fit the models and create a tibble
  Models<-fit_time_series_models(data_stationary) 
  # Store the names of the different tables
  names_model <-c(Models$Model_name)
  
  Return_data<-Returns_value(data_stationary)
  # Set the names for each model to be sued while accesing the forecast for each model
  Return_data<-setNames(Return_data,names_model)
  backtest_output<-backtest_strategy(test_data,Return_data,names_model)
   return(list(Models,backtest_output))
}

From the findings, the 1-day time series emerged as the most effective for predicting Bitcoin prices, exhibiting lower Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) and higher Information Coefficient (IC). This indicates that longer time intervals, such as daily data, provide more stable and reliable signals, reducing noise and short-term volatility. The reduced noise in daily data allows for clearer trend identification, making it easier for models to capture longer-term movements in the BTC/USD exchange rate.

Comparison with Shorter Time Intervals

When comparing this to one-minute or five-minute intervals, the higher frequency data tends to be noisier, making it challenging for predictive models to achieve the same level of accuracy. While high-frequency data can be beneficial for capturing intraday movements, the increased noise often leads to higher MAPE values, reflecting less accurate predictions. Short-term fluctuations in the cryptocurrency market may overwhelm the ability to discern meaningful trends, which affects the IC negatively as well, showing weaker correlation with future price changes.

Similarly, one-hour intervals also contain more noise than daily data, though they can offer a compromise between granularity and signal clarity. They may provide some insights for medium-term trading strategies but still fall short of the stability and predictability seen in daily data.

Time Series Theory Implications From a time series theory perspective, longer intervals allow for better trend following and smoother autoregressive behavior. The seasonality and cyclicality that are fundamental in time series modeling are more prominent in daily data, which helps improve the model’s predictive capabilities. Lower-frequency data often reduces the impact of stochastic noise and improves the signal-to-noise ratio, which is critical for making more accurate forecasts.

In contrast, higher-frequency data (e.g., minute-level data) is more prone to noise from market microstructure effects, such as order book imbalances and liquidity shocks, leading to less reliable predictive models.
